Do we need more Highly Rated Professors at UMD?¶

At the University of Maryland - College Park (UMD), students hope to be able produce "fearless ideas". As a result, most expect help and assistance from professors/lecturers who can easily explain and teach them lecture material. At the same time, they expect their skills to be challenged through projects and examinations that are within their potential. However, how many professors truly meet student expectations? Does UMD need more or does it already have a fair amount of good professors?

In order to clean the data, I have performed the following:

The Salary Data
1. In the salary data, salaries were formated as type strings. In order to make further operations that will be performed later in this tutorial, the strings got converted into type float by using the apply() function.
2. Any employee that was recorded more than once in the data was removed using the drop_duplicates() function.

An issue with the salary data was that because the salary data does NOT contain any ratings and the aim of the project is to find good professors, it became neccessary to collect another dataset that contains the ratings for every (or most) professors. The a well-known website that contains data on professor ratings specifically of UMD is called PlanetTerp

Planetterp is a website where students at UMD can place reviews and ratings for various professors that teach a particular course. It is a useful tool for students at UMD especially those who are signing up for classes since they can search up either a professor or courseID and determine which professor is rated as "good" for a particular course. The rating is based of a five star system where a professor with rating 1 or 1.5 is deemed bad while a professor with a rating of 4.5 or 5.0 is deemed excellent. More information about planetterp can be seen here: https://planetterp.com/

The Rating Data
1. To receive the rating data from planetterp, an array (requests) was intialized and all of the website content was scraped using the requests() function. Due to the unknown waiting period to load the data, tdqm() was used to track the progress of the data loading. Tqdm is a library in python that allows visualization of how much progress the code has done as well as providing an estimate time of how long it will take to execute the code. View more information about tqdm here: https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2021/05/how-to-use-progress-bars-in-python/
2. After loading the data into an array, the array was organized into a dataframe and was mereged with the salaries dataframe based on the professor's name
3. Because the subject of interest are professors rather than Teaching assistants, only the rows containing professors were selected. 4. Finally, rows with all missing ratings (labelled as NaN) were removed.

Data Representation¶

In order to best represent the data, I have chosen to use a histogram. A histogram is a plot that shows the frequency of a variable is
present in a dataset. I chose this kind of representation because this tutorial is concerned about how many professors are actually "good"
at UMD and whether UMD needs more good professors. Thus, the best way to visualize this scheme is to use a histogram that shows the number
of professors with higher/lower ratings.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

After looking at the histogram that displayed the number of professors with each rating two main questions have arised in my mind:
1. Although most professors seem to be rated very highly, most of them might be part of the same department or most of these professors might be from the same kind of subject such as STEM. Thus, my first question are all departments have evenly distributed ratings and if not, which department seems to be prioritized and which seems to be undermined?
2. Do professors get "better" with their reviews as their salaries increase?

In this section, I will try to explore these variables and answer these questions!

There are certain outliers, such as the blue cell showing the correlation between the number of reviews and the CMNS department. But for the sake of this project, what seems more interesting is that there seems to be some positive correlation for the average rating row, specifically between rating and certain departments such as the ARHU, SVPAAP, etc. There are also a few negative correlations such as between the average rating and the CMNS department. I can use a hypothesis test to see if these correlations are significant.

Hypothesis Testing¶

Hypothesis Statement: There is a correlation present between department and average rating

Null Hypothesis: There is no correlation present between department and average rating

The hypothesis test I am going to utilize is the ANOVA test. ANOVA tests allow you to determine the statistical difference between two or more categorical groups using the variance. Because I hypothesized that there is a correlation present between department and average rating, the ANOVA test is the most suitble way to test my hypothesis in comparison to other statistical tests since department is a categorical variable. To look into more information about ANOVA tests, you can refer to this link: https://www.tibco.com/reference-center/what-is-analysis-of-variance-anova

After using a ANOVA test to see the statistical differences between each department and average rating, I found that the CMNS, ENGR, PLCY, SVPAAP and VPSA departments have p-values (shown as P > |t|) below 0.05, while the rest of the departments have p-values above 0.05 which means my hypothesis is somewhat correct but the null hypothesis is also somewhat correct as well. Because of this, I cannot completely reject the null hypothesis.

Machine Learning¶

Since my hypothesis seems somewhat right and wrong at the same time, I became curious as to how accurate would a machine learning algorithm would predict a professor's ratign based solely on their department. The machine learning algorithm that I will be using to classify a professor's rating based on their department is a Logistic Regression. A logistic regression is a classification algorithm that assigns observations based on a discrete set of classes (e.g obese, not obese,etc.). You can view more information about logistic regressions here: https://www.javatpoint.com/logistic-regression-in-machine-learning

A logistic regression would be best suited to predict a professor's rating since I am using a discrete class of departments and assigning that professor a rating based on those classes.

After using a logistic regression model, I found that the accuracy (how correct my machine learning algortihm was) for my model is super low in which my algorithm was able to predict only about 29% of the data correctly, and the logistic regression model completely failed on the testing set. This confirms the fact that a professor's department is in fact not related to their rating (which also intuitively makes sense) and that the null hypothesis is more correct compared to my alternative hypothesis.

Communication of Insight¶
